#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:1
msgid "`T: 'a` inference in structs"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.31](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.31-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:5
msgid ""
"An annotation in the form of `T: 'a`, where `T` is either a type or another "
"lifetime, is called an _\"outlives\"_ requirement. Note that _\"outlives\"_ "
"also implies `'a: 'a`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/inference-in-structs.md:9
msgid ""
"One way in which edition 2018 helps you out in maintaining flow when writing "
"programs is by removing the need to explicitly annotate these `T: 'a` "
"outlives requirements in `struct` definitions. Instead, the requirements "
"will be inferred from the fields present in the definitions."
msgstr ""

